sults from later conceptions of literary history. Before the modern era, there existed a conceptual gap between an author and a writer. A pre-modern Chinese text could have had both an author and a writer, or even multiple authors and multiple writers. This work is the first study addressing these issues by more systematically emphasizing the connection of the text, the author, and the religious and sociopolitical settings in which these issues were embedded. It is expected to constitute a palpable contribution to Chinese studies and the discipline of philology in general  afunded by Jao Tsung-I Academy of Sinology  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aAuthorshipxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChinese literatureyTo 221 B.CxHistory and criticism. 0aChinese literatureyTo 221 B.C.xHistory and criticism. 0aTransmission of textszChinaxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aAutorschaft. 4aChinesische Texte. 4aMethodik. 4aSinologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Authorship.2bisacsh  aConfucius.  aLiu An.  aSima Qian.  aYellow Emperor.2 aJao Tsung-I Academy of Sinologyefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2018z97831107195500 cEPUBz97815015051950 cprintz978150151435740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501505133zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501505133zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501505133.jpg  a978-3-11-071955-0 DG Plus eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA